  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How should I prepare for physics NEET 2017 and from where do I start ?",
  "response": "Preparing for the physics section of the NEET (National Eligibility cum Entrance Test) 2017 requires a structured approach and dedication. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you prepare effectively:\n\n### 1. **Understand the Syllabus**\n   First, get familiar with the NEET physics syllabus. The syllabus includes topics from class 11 and 12 physics. Key topics include:\n   - Mechanics\n   - Heat and Thermodynamics\n   - Electrostatics and Current Electricity\n   - Magnetism and Electromagnetic Induction\n   - Optics\n   - Modern Physics (including atoms and nuclei)\n\n### 2. **Gather Study Materials**\n   - **Textbooks**: Use standard textbooks like H.C. Verma\u2019s \u201cConcepts of Physics\u201d for theory and practice, and D.C. Pandey\u2019s series for additional practice problems.\n   - **NCERT Books**: These are crucial as NEET questions are often based on the concepts explained in these books.\n   - **Previous Years' Papers**: Solve NEET and AIPMT previous years' papers to understand the exam pattern and type of questions asked.\n\n### 3. **Create a Study Plan**\n   - **Allocate Time**: Divide your study time equally between class 11 and class 12 topics.\n   - **Daily Schedule**: Set specific hours each day for physics, ensuring you have time for both theory and problem-solving.\n   - **Weekly Reviews**: Dedicate time at the end of each week to review what you have learned and practice with mock tests.\n\n### 4. **Study Techniques**\n   - **Conceptual Understanding**: Start with understanding the basic concepts thoroughly. Use diagrams and animations to visualize complex processes.\n   - **Practice Regularly**: Solve a variety of problems ranging from simple to complex. Use the problems in H.C. Verma and additional problem sets from D.C. Pandey.\n   - **Note-taking**: Keep a notebook for important formulas, derivations, and concepts. Review these notes regularly.\n\n### 5. **Focus Areas**\n   - **Mechanics and Kinematics**: These are fundamental and carry significant weightage.\n   - **Electromagnetism**: This is another important area that often appears in the exam.\n   - **Modern Physics**: Concepts like radioactivity, photoelectric effect, and atomic structure are frequently tested.\n\n### 6. **Mock Tests and Revision**\n   - **Mock Tests**: Regularly take full-length mock tests to assess your preparation level. Analyze your performance to identify weak areas.\n   - **Revision**: Keep revising topics regularly. Use your notes and flashcards for quick reviews.\n\n### 7. **Additional Resources**\n   - **Online Platforms**: Websites like Khan Academy, Physics Classroom, and YouTube channels like those by physicswallah can be helpful for conceptual understanding.\n   - **Coaching**: If possible, join a coaching institute or take online coaching for structured guidance and doubt clearing.\n\n### 8. **Stay Healthy and Motivated**\n   - **Balanced Lifestyle**: Ensure you get enough sleep, eat healthily, and take short breaks during study sessions.\n   - **Stay Motivated**: Set small, achievable goals, and reward yourself for reaching them.\n\n### Where to Start?\n   Start with the basics from class 11 physics, particularly mechanics and thermodynamics. Here's a suggested starting point:\n   - **Class 11**: Begin with the chapters on physical world and measurement, kinematics, laws of motion, work, energy and power, and then move to rotation and gravitation.\n   - **Class 12**: After gaining a good grasp of class 11 topics, start with electrostatics, current electricity, and magnetism.\n\nBy following these steps and maintaining a consistent study schedule, you can prepare effectively for the physics section of NEET 2017. Good luck!",
